1.	What is the purpose of using CUDA to perform addition of two large vectors? 
The purpose of using CUDA is to speed up vector addition by utilizing the parallel processing power of the GPU. 
In CUDA: 
	Multiple GPU threads add vector elements simultaneously 
	Large computations are completed much faster than CPU execution 
Example: 
C[i]=A[i]+B[i] 
Each thread computes one element independently. 
Benefits: 
	Faster execution 
Better performance for large datasets 
	Efficient parallel computation  
2.	How do you allocate memory for the vectors on the device using CUDA? 
Memory on the GPU device is allocated using cudaMalloc(). 
Syntax: 
cudaMalloc((void**)&A, size); Example: 
cudaMalloc((void**)&d_A, size); 
cudaMalloc((void**)&d_B, size); cudaMalloc((void**)&d_C, size); Where: 
•	d_A, d_B, d_C are device pointers 
•	size is memory size in bytes  
3.	How do you launch the CUDA kernel to perform the addition of two large vectors? 
CUDA kernels are launched using the <<<blocks, threads>>> syntax. 
Syntax: 
kernel<<<number_of_blocks, threads_per_block>>>(); Example: 
vectorAdd<<<256, 256>>>(d_A, d_B, d_C); 
Where: 
•	First value = number of blocks 
•	Second value = number of threads per block 
Each thread performs addition for one vector element.  
4.	How can you optimize the performance of the CUDA program for adding two large vectors? 
Optimization Techniques: 
1.	Use proper number of threads and blocks 
Efficient thread configuration improves GPU utilization.  
2.	Minimize memory transfer 
Reduce data transfer between CPU and GPU because it increases overhead.  
3.	Use coalesced memory access 
Access consecutive memory locations for faster GPU memory performance. 
4.	Use shared memory 
Shared memory is faster than global memory and improves speed.  
5.	Increase parallelism 
Use more threads to fully utilize GPU cores.  
6.	Avoid uecessary synchronization 
Too much synchronization reduces performance.  
7.	Optimize kernel execution 
Reduce branching and inefficient instructions inside kernels. 
